    "Background": {
      "text": "The piriformis muscle acts as an external rotator, weak abductor, and weak flexor of the hip\nIt originates from the anterior sacrum and inserts on the greater trochanter of the femur\nThe sciatic nerve typically exits the greater sciatic foramen deep along the inferior surface of the piriformis muscle, but in approximately 20% of people, the sciatic nerve pierces the piriformis muscle\n[1]\nLocal inflammation of the piriformis can cause muscular compression or irritation of the sciatic nerve causing local or radicular pain",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Pain in area of buttocks and hamstring muscles\nWorsened by sitting, climbing stairs, or squatting",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
